00:10:00.850 --> 00:10:04.300
&gt;&gt;Samuel Thomas: Yup, and we
have the valley areas and we have

00:10:04.300 --> 00:10:06.570
of course the edge
of the Sahara Desert.

00:10:06.570 --> 00:10:10.740
All of these different
zones juxtaposition

00:10:10.740 --> 00:10:14.990
in one relatively small land area.

00:10:14.990 --> 00:10:20.670
So, this is kind of
at a fundamental core

00:10:20.670 --> 00:10:23.720
of Moroccan diversity, I would say.

00:10:23.720 --> 00:10:31.230 position:56%
To move on, you can see over here
the reason I've included this map is

00:10:31.230 --> 00:10:37.690 position:56%
to talk a bit about Morocco as a
conduit point between East and West,

00:10:37.690 --> 00:10:43.780
because Moroccan history--
and this is I point

00:10:43.780 --> 00:10:45.480
out to the population flows.

00:10:45.480 --> 00:10:50.030
Moroccan history being on the
cusp of North Africa there,

00:10:50.030 --> 00:10:58.420
on the farthest western side, has
seen people traveling through it

00:10:58.420 --> 00:11:03.370 position:56%
as kind of a nexus point and I think
that's very fundamental as well

00:11:03.370 --> 00:11:05.580
to Moroccan culture--

00:11:05.580 --> 00:11:11.090
to the development of Moroccan
culture over the centuries.

00:11:12.290 --> 00:11:16.110
The notion of Morocco as isolated

00:11:16.110 --> 00:11:20.770
from the Iberian Peninsula
is relatively recent.

00:11:20.770 --> 00:11:28.860 position:56%
Morocco would-- The flows between
people across the Iberian Peninsula,

00:11:28.860 --> 00:11:30.500
I mean, across the
Strait of Gibraltar

00:11:30.500 --> 00:11:34.930
into the Iberian Peninsula is
very common in earlier centuries.

00:11:34.930 --> 00:11:41.110
In fact, if anybody is up
on Andalus history, right,

00:11:41.110 --> 00:11:48.330
the founding of the Andalusian
Caliphate in Cordoba was

00:11:48.330 --> 00:11:54.800 position:56%
with the help of Berber mercenary
armies, Amazigh armies from Morocco.

00:11:54.800 --> 00:12:04.320
In fact, Gibraltar is titled after
the general who led these armies,

00:12:04.320 --> 00:12:09.810
Tariq ibn Ziyad, and that's why
it's called Jabal Tariq the Mount

00:12:09.810 --> 00:12:13.750
of Tariq, Gibraltar.

00:12:13.750 --> 00:12:15.900
Furthermore, as we continue

00:12:15.900 --> 00:12:21.950
into later centuries we certainly
have empires actually being

00:12:21.950 --> 00:12:26.050
expressed centered in Morocco
and expressed across the Strait

00:12:26.050 --> 00:12:32.470 position:56%
of Gibraltar, the Al Mourabitoun and
the Al Muwahhidun are both centered

00:12:32.470 --> 00:12:36.100
in Morocco, but expressing
their power northward.

00:12:36.100 --> 00:12:41.710
So, point being that this is kind
of a nexus point and has been

00:12:41.710 --> 00:12:46.390
for a long time for a lot of
diversity to travel through.

00:12:46.390 --> 00:12:49.160
And, of course, with that is going

00:12:49.160 --> 00:12:52.770
to come a diversity in
cultural expressions.

00:12:57.570 --> 00:13:03.400
So to turn now to the diversity
in my area of interest with--

00:13:03.400 --> 00:13:08.020 position:56%
in terms of musical expression would
be the Moroccan musical cultures,

00:13:08.020 --> 00:13:09.320
right?

00:13:09.320 --> 00:13:16.490 position:56%
So, what do I mean by Arab, Amazigh,
Andalusi, Gnaoua musical cultures?

00:13:16.490 --> 00:13:19.920 position:56%
So, included in this would be, well,

00:13:19.920 --> 00:13:23.700 position:56%
with the Arab musical cultures would
be the kinds of things developed

00:13:23.700 --> 00:13:28.470
in the classical style
of music centered

00:13:28.470 --> 00:13:35.080
around Arabic composition both in
terms of the poetry and in terms

00:13:35.080 --> 00:13:38.810
of the music itself;
systems of music.

00:13:38.810 --> 00:13:42.800
So, this would be developing
in Abbasid,

00:13:42.800 --> 00:13:48.040
Baghdad finding its way westward
and be developing in Andalus

00:13:48.040 --> 00:13:49.750
and finding its way southward.

00:13:49.750 --> 00:13:55.510
To this very day the Arab classical
music tradition in Morocco,

00:13:55.510 --> 00:14:05.330
al-Ala al-Andalusia, is
markedly different from the

00:14:05.330 --> 00:14:08.120
"Arab classical styles"
that are in Algeria

00:14:08.120 --> 00:14:10.640
and Tunisia further to the east.

00:14:10.640 --> 00:14:14.700
The Ottoman Empire stopped
at the doorstep of Morocco.

00:14:14.700 --> 00:14:16.580
So, the patrimony

00:14:16.580 --> 00:14:24.590 position:56%
of the Andalusian-Moroccan classical
music sphere has been kept more

00:14:24.590 --> 00:14:27.990
intact in Morocco.

00:14:27.990 --> 00:14:32.410
So, this is expressed in the
modes, the musical modes,

00:14:32.410 --> 00:14:36.410
in the rhythmic modes,
certainly in the song texts

00:14:36.410 --> 00:14:38.610
and in the melodies themselves.

00:14:38.610 --> 00:14:43.290
So, that I would-- I classify
there under the Arab styles.

00:14:43.290 --> 00:14:48.230
Amazigh styles would be the
again the native communities

00:14:48.230 --> 00:14:52.860
that primarily centered outside
the cities in the villages

00:14:52.860 --> 00:15:01.160
or in the smaller towns and there
