00:17:29.820 --> 00:17:37.100
In terms of melody-making, there
are different modes for melody.

00:17:37.100 --> 00:17:40.100
So we have, you know, in the West,

00:17:40.100 --> 00:17:44.990
in Western classical styles
we have modes typically based

00:17:44.990 --> 00:17:55.640 position:56%
around-welcome-- and typically
based around like a harmonic system.

00:17:55.640 --> 00:18:01.620
So, for instance, you know,
the Do-Re-Mi-Fa-So-La-Ti-Do.

00:18:01.620 --> 00:18:05.390
So we have this and then we have
another mode built upon that

00:18:05.390 --> 00:18:08.640
but it's all harmonically
driven, right?

00:18:08.640 --> 00:18:13.250
Whereas, in Moroccan music
it's all melodically driven,

00:18:13.250 --> 00:18:18.550
so that the melody takes absolute
precedence there really is no

00:18:18.550 --> 00:18:24.840
harmony per se to play chords
behind it or something like that.

00:18:24.840 --> 00:18:26.750
It's really about knowing
the melodies.

00:18:26.750 --> 00:18:28.830
Now the melodies do come
out of certain modes

00:18:28.830 --> 00:18:31.700
like a Do-Re-Mi-Fa-So-La-Ti-Do
kind of thing,

00:18:31.700 --> 00:18:35.750
but you could have two modes
that have the exact same notes

00:18:35.750 --> 00:18:38.430
but different notes
are emphasized, right?

00:18:38.430 --> 00:18:45.150
So, you could emphasize
Do-RE-Mi-Fa-So, that's one,

00:18:45.150 --> 00:18:51.370
or it could be
Do-Re-Mi-FA-So-Fa-Mi-Re-Do.

00:18:51.370 --> 00:18:54.010
And that's a different setup.

00:18:54.010 --> 00:18:59.920
So how the notes are emphasized
makes big difference in terms

00:18:59.920 --> 00:19:02.690
of the system, the
systemizing of the melody.

00:19:02.690 --> 00:19:05.760
Then, in terms of melody-making
the--

00:19:05.760 --> 00:19:11.920 position:56%
it's all melodically driven music so
that the melodies can be repetitive

00:19:11.920 --> 00:19:16.420
and then changing to another melody
quite making a stark contrast

00:19:16.420 --> 00:19:20.520
or the melodies can be more
complex in the classical tradition.

00:19:20.520 --> 00:19:25.470
And the way that musicians
are really trained are

00:19:25.470 --> 00:19:30.120
to really learn these melodies
internally to the degree

00:19:30.120 --> 00:19:34.080
that you can begin to play
around these melodies.

00:19:34.080 --> 00:19:39.780 position:56%
And what happens out of that is very
different from the Western context.

00:19:39.780 --> 00:19:42.640
So, I mean, I'm putting this in
relief to the Western context

00:19:42.640 --> 00:19:47.300
but the Western classical style
where the harmony is driving a lot

00:19:47.300 --> 00:19:50.540
of this and you have a
harmonic motion or, you know,

00:19:50.540 --> 00:19:54.200
like the sonata form for instance
where you have a change of pitch

00:19:54.200 --> 00:19:59.090 position:56%
in fact at another point in the
movement is all harmonically driven.

00:19:59.090 --> 00:20:03.090 position:56%
In this music being that it's all
melodically driven there are moments

00:20:03.090 --> 00:20:04.390
of harmony.

00:20:04.390 --> 00:20:07.490
So the question is, well, what
are these moments of harmony

00:20:07.490 --> 00:20:09.350
and how are they determined, right?

00:20:09.350 --> 00:20:12.170
If they're not determined
in advance,

00:20:12.170 --> 00:20:13.470
then how are they determined?

00:20:13.470 --> 00:20:15.530
They are determined
in a heterophonic way.

00:20:15.530 --> 00:20:18.540
So, for those of you that may
not be familiar with that term,

00:20:18.540 --> 00:20:23.110
heterophony is when you have a
classroom of kids trying to sing

00:20:23.110 --> 00:20:26.460
"Mary Had a Little
Lamb" together, OK?

00:20:26.460 --> 00:20:30.100
Or, if we all try to
sing, I don't know,

00:20:30.100 --> 00:20:31.990
"Stars Spangled Banner"
together, right now,

00:20:31.990 --> 00:20:34.260
I think we would experience
some heterophony.

00:20:34.260 --> 00:20:38.560 position:56%
And that just means that we end up--
we all know the melody but we end

00:20:38.560 --> 00:20:43.270
up sort of expressing it timewise
a little different and we end

00:20:43.270 --> 00:20:47.280
up getting these variations
that happen and so, you know,

00:20:47.280 --> 00:20:51.290
you move on to the next note at a
different time than you do and out

00:20:51.290 --> 00:20:53.740
of that creates harmony of course.

00:20:53.740 --> 00:20:57.730
And that harmony then becomes
like an emergent quality rather

00:20:57.730 --> 00:20:59.860
than a predetermined quality.

00:20:59.860 --> 00:21:04.170
So, listening to Moroccan
music and understanding it

00:21:04.170 --> 00:21:07.800
that way I think is
a very important key.

00:21:07.800 --> 00:21:12.040
So that is the melodic approach.

00:21:12.040 --> 00:21:13.590
Language systems.

00:21:13.590 --> 00:21:17.470
Well, there are certainly styles

00:21:17.470 --> 00:21:24.740
where the language is the higher
level composition in terms

00:21:24.740 --> 00:21:30.260
of the poetry and the expression
of ideas of religious significance

00:21:30.260 --> 00:21:35.380
such as, you know, texts
taken directly from the Quran

00:21:35.380 --> 00:21:43.290
or in Hebrew the poets often
would be incorporating segments

00:21:43.290 --> 00:21:47.240
from the Torah or from
the Tanakh and weaving

00:21:47.240 --> 00:21:51.650
that together with other ideas.

00:21:51.650 --> 00:21:56.500
So, that's kind of like I
would say a high register.

00:21:56.500 --> 00:22:03.820
Then you have a more colloquial
style language expression

00:22:03.820 --> 00:22:08.680
that is typically in Arabic
and then you have, of course,

00:22:08.680 --> 00:22:11.730
songs in Amazigh, as
I mentioned before.

00:22:11.730 --> 00:22:14.950 position:56%
You have songs that are even mixing.

00:22:14.950 --> 00:22:21.650 position:56%
And one important category to point
out would be the Judeo-Español songs

00:22:21.650 --> 00:22:26.630
that are a unique dialect
in Morocco.

00:22:26.630 --> 00:22:31.380
So the Jews that were
part of the Expulsion,

00:22:31.380 --> 00:22:36.360
the migration from the Expulsion
of Spain in 1492, many of which,

00:22:36.360 --> 00:22:40.050
of course, settled in Morocco
because of its proximity to Iberia,

00:22:40.050 --> 00:22:46.860
to Spain, were bringing a
version of Spanish, right?

00:22:46.860 --> 00:22:52.330
And that version of Spanish
would be mixed with Hebrew words

00:22:52.330 --> 00:22:56.730
and as it would get into
Morocco it would be even mixed

00:22:56.730 --> 00:23:00.740 position:56%
with Hebrew words and even sometimes
Arabic words and you would have

00:23:00.740 --> 00:23:04.930
out of this then a unique dialect
that would develop over centuries

00:23:04.930 --> 00:23:10.250
in contradistinction, let's
say, from that which developed

00:23:10.250 --> 00:23:16.480
by the Sephardic Jews in
Turkey, or in Amsterdam.

00:23:16.480 --> 00:23:20.570
So that is part of
the language, too.

