01:12:53.270 --> 01:12:55.500
And first of all, the flows
of Moroccan immigrants

01:12:55.500 --> 01:12:58.050
to America have continued
over decades.

01:12:58.050 --> 01:13:03.460
This particular beginning or
inception of the community

01:13:03.460 --> 01:13:07.640
in Brooklyn was a specifically
isolated kind of event in context,

01:13:07.640 --> 01:13:12.810
but in the '70s-- '60s and '70s
there are more folks coming

01:13:12.810 --> 01:13:14.110
to America.

01:13:14.110 --> 01:13:17.210
Now, the community at least in
America is really includes a lot

01:13:17.210 --> 01:13:21.940
of Moroccans directly from
Morocco; Moroccans from Israel;

01:13:21.940 --> 01:13:26.300
and Moroccans from France, so
they're kind of intermingling.

01:13:26.300 --> 01:13:33.010
So in terms of languages, well, if
you ever visit a Moroccan synagogue

01:13:33.010 --> 01:13:38.100
on a Saturday morning, you could
hear a French coming in this ear,

01:13:38.100 --> 01:13:42.300
and Arabic maybe in this ear and
Hebrew in this ear and English

01:13:42.300 --> 01:13:49.610
in this ear, you know, you
don't have enough ears to listen

01:13:49.610 --> 01:13:53.590
to all the languages
that are spinning about.

01:13:53.590 --> 01:13:57.230
So, I do think in terms
of keeping language

01:13:57.230 --> 01:14:01.840
or keeping musical traditions
alive, the different kinds

01:14:01.840 --> 01:14:07.270
of expressions are happening within
the community, which of course,

01:14:07.270 --> 01:14:09.240
is centered around
the synagogue life

01:14:09.240 --> 01:14:14.200
and therefore the liturgy reiterate
so much of this and the other kind

01:14:14.200 --> 01:14:15.880
